### EC-OPS — Complex End-to-End Scenarios
### Run these in sequence (top to bottom) — copy IDs between steps
### Requires VS Code REST Client extension (humao.rest-client)
###
### Authentication: get a token from auth.http first, then paste it below.

@baseUrl = http://localhost:8002
@token = PASTE_ACCESS_TOKEN_HERE


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SCENARIO 1: Full order lifecycle
# Create → verify PENDING → cancel (soft-delete) → verify CANCELLED
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

### Step 1.1 — Create order
# @name lifecycle_create
POST {{baseUrl}}/orders
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "customer_name": "Lifecycle Test",
  "items": [
    { "product_name": "Test Item", "quantity": 1, "price": "10.00" }
  ]
}

###

### Step 1.2 — Verify it is PENDING
# Copy the id from Step 1.1 response
@lifecycle_id = REPLACE_WITH_ID_FROM_1_1

GET {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{lifecycle_id}}
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 1.3 — Confirm it appears in PENDING list
GET {{baseUrl}}/orders?status=PENDING
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 1.4 — Cancel it (soft-delete — sets status to CANCELLED)
DELETE {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{lifecycle_id}}
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 1.5 — Verify it is retained with status CANCELLED (200, not 404)
GET {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{lifecycle_id}}
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 1.6 — Confirm it no longer appears in PENDING list
GET {{baseUrl}}/orders?status=PENDING
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 1.7 — Confirm it appears in CANCELLED list
GET {{baseUrl}}/orders?status=CANCELLED
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SCENARIO 2: Full status lifecycle — PENDING → PROCESSING → SHIPPED → DELIVERED
# Demonstrates the PATCH /orders/{id}/status endpoint walking through every
# valid transition in the state machine. Mirrors what an AI agent would do
# when processing and fulfilling an order.
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

### Step 2.1 — Create order (starts as PENDING)
# @name status_lifecycle_create
POST {{baseUrl}}/orders
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "customer_name": "Status Lifecycle Test",
  "items": [
    { "product_name": "Laptop", "quantity": 1, "price": "999.00" }
  ]
}

###

### Step 2.2 — Verify initial status is PENDING
# Copy the id from Step 2.1 response
@status_lifecycle_id = REPLACE_WITH_ID_FROM_2_1

GET {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{status_lifecycle_id}}
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 2.3 — Advance to PROCESSING (warehouse picked up the order)
PATCH {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{status_lifecycle_id}}/status
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "status": "PROCESSING"
}

###

### Step 2.4 — Verify status is PROCESSING and updated_at is set
GET {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{status_lifecycle_id}}
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 2.5 — Advance to SHIPPED (carrier collected)
PATCH {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{status_lifecycle_id}}/status
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "status": "SHIPPED"
}

###

### Step 2.6 — Confirm it now appears in SHIPPED list
GET {{baseUrl}}/orders?status=SHIPPED
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 2.7 — Advance to DELIVERED (customer received package)
PATCH {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{status_lifecycle_id}}/status
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "status": "DELIVERED"
}

###

### Step 2.8 — Verify terminal state: DELIVERED
GET {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{status_lifecycle_id}}
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 2.9 — Attempt invalid backward transition DELIVERED → SHIPPED → expect 422
PATCH {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{status_lifecycle_id}}/status
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "status": "SHIPPED"
}

###

### Step 2.10 — Attempt to cancel a DELIVERED order → expect 409
DELETE {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{status_lifecycle_id}}
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SCENARIO 3: Bulk creation + status filtering
# Create several orders, filter by status, verify counts
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

### Step 2.1 — Create order A
POST {{baseUrl}}/orders
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "customer_name": "Bulk Customer A",
  "items": [{ "product_name": "Item A1", "quantity": 2, "price": "15.00" }]
}

###

### Step 2.2 — Create order B
POST {{baseUrl}}/orders
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "customer_name": "Bulk Customer B",
  "items": [
    { "product_name": "Item B1", "quantity": 1, "price": "25.00" },
    { "product_name": "Item B2", "quantity": 3, "price": "8.50" }
  ]
}

###

### Step 2.3 — Create order C
POST {{baseUrl}}/orders
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "customer_name": "Bulk Customer C",
  "items": [{ "product_name": "Item C1", "quantity": 5, "price": "3.99" }]
}

###

### Step 2.4 — List all orders (should include A, B, C as PENDING)
GET {{baseUrl}}/orders
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 2.5 — List only PENDING
GET {{baseUrl}}/orders?status=PENDING
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SCENARIO 3: Cancel race — try to cancel a PROCESSING order
# Create an order, wait for scheduler to promote it (5 min),
# then attempt cancel → expect 409
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

### Step 3.1 — Create order to be promoted
POST {{baseUrl}}/orders
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "customer_name": "Processing Race",
  "items": [{ "product_name": "Race Item", "quantity": 1, "price": "99.00" }]
}

###

### Step 3.2 — After 5 min, verify it is now PROCESSING
# Copy id from Step 3.1
@race_id = REPLACE_WITH_ID_FROM_3_1

GET {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{race_id}}
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 3.3 — Attempt to cancel a PROCESSING order → expect 409
DELETE {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{race_id}}
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SCENARIO 4: Agent creates order, REST API reads it
# Natural language → agent → SSE → verify via REST
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

### Step 4.1 — Ask agent to create order
GET {{baseUrl}}/agent/stream?message=Create%20an%20order%20for%20Grace%20with%202%20yoga%20mats%20at%20%2422.00%20each%20and%201%20water%20bottle%20at%20%2412.50
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 4.2 — Confirm via REST — should appear in PENDING list
GET {{baseUrl}}/orders?status=PENDING
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 4.3 — Get the order Grace placed (copy id from PENDING list)
@grace_order_id = REPLACE_WITH_ID_FROM_4_2

GET {{baseUrl}}/orders/{{grace_order_id}}
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SCENARIO 5: A2A fire-and-forget with polling
# Submit → poll until completed → read result
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

### Step 5.1 — Submit task (returns 202 immediately)
# @name a2a_scenario
POST {{baseUrl}}/a2a/tasks/send
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "message": "Create an order for Henry with 1 ergonomic chair at $350.00 and list all pending orders"
}

###

### Step 5.2 — Poll immediately (likely still pending)
@a2a_task_id = REPLACE_WITH_TASK_ID_FROM_5_1

GET {{baseUrl}}/a2a/tasks/{{a2a_task_id}}
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 5.3 — Poll again after a few seconds (should be completed)
GET {{baseUrl}}/a2a/tasks/{{a2a_task_id}}
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

###

### Step 5.4 — Verify the order was created via REST
GET {{baseUrl}}/orders?status=PENDING
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SCENARIO 6: Multi-item order price edge cases
# Zero-price item (free gift), max quantity, high-value order
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

### Step 6.1 — Order with a free item (price = 0.00, allowed by ge=0)
POST {{baseUrl}}/orders
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "customer_name": "Promo Customer",
  "items": [
    { "product_name": "Premium Headphones", "quantity": 1, "price": "199.99" },
    { "product_name": "Free Carry Case",    "quantity": 1, "price": "0.00" }
  ]
}

###

### Step 6.2 — High-value order
POST {{baseUrl}}/orders
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "customer_name": "Enterprise Buyer",
  "items": [
    { "product_name": "Server Rack",       "quantity": 2,  "price": "1299.99" },
    { "product_name": "Network Switch",    "quantity": 4,  "price": "459.00" },
    { "product_name": "UPS Battery",       "quantity": 2,  "price": "349.50" },
    { "product_name": "Patch Panel",       "quantity": 10, "price": "89.99" }
  ]
}

###

### Step 6.3 — Large quantity, low unit price
POST {{baseUrl}}/orders
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}

{
  "customer_name": "Stationery Bulk",
  "items": [
    { "product_name": "Ballpoint Pen",  "quantity": 100, "price": "0.49" },
    { "product_name": "Sticky Notes",  "quantity": 50,  "price": "1.99" },
    { "product_name": "Paper Clip Box", "quantity": 20,  "price": "2.49" }
  ]
}
